### ðŸ§‘â€ðŸ« **Teacher:**  
Barun beta, single aur double quotes dono ka kaam hai **special characters ko protect karna**, lekin unka **behaviour different** hota hai.

---

## ðŸ“¦ Single Quotes `' '`

> **Everything is taken *literally***  
> Har character **as-is** treat hota hai â€” koi variable ya command expand nahi hoti

### ðŸ” Example:

```bash
echo '$HOME'
```

ðŸ§¾ Output:
```
$HOME
```

âœ… Variable print **nahi hua** â€” uska naam hi as it is print ho gaya  
â›”ï¸ No variable expansion

---

## âœ¨ Double Quotes `" "`

> **Variables and command substitution allowed**  
> Shell kuch cheezon ko **expand karta hai**

### ðŸ” Example:

```bash
echo "$HOME"
```

ðŸ§¾ Output:
```
/home/barun
```

âœ… Variable expand ho gaya  
ðŸŸ¢ `$HOME` ki value aa gayi

---

## ðŸ“Š Comparison Table

| Feature                    | `'Single Quotes'`           | `"Double Quotes"`            |
|---------------------------|-----------------------------|------------------------------|
| Variable Expansion        | âŒ No                       | âœ… Yes                        |
| Command Substitution      | âŒ No                       | âœ… Yes (`$(...)`)            |
| Literal Characters        | âœ… All preserved            | ðŸ”¶ Some preserved             |
| Escape needed inside?     | âŒ Not usually              | âœ… Yes (for `$`, `"`, `\`)   |

---

## ðŸ’¡ Easy Trick to Remember:

> ðŸ§  **Single quote = Strong wall**  
> âŒ Koi variable ya command andar ghus nahi sakti

> ðŸ§  **Double quote = Flexible window**  
> âœ… Variables aur commands andar dikhte hain

